defaultPERSONAL EXPERIENCES AS FATHER OF A YOUNG FAMILY
defaultComputers and the internet are a fundamental part of life for our children, as they are
default for any children in the UK today. In a way that we adults did not, they are growing up with computer technology all around them.  Indeed, it is astounding how quickly
default—
defaultalmost naturally
default—
defaultthey pick it up.  My daughter has just turned 5 and cannot yet read
default, but even she can navigate with remarkable speed 
defaultthrough 
defaultwebsites 
defaultshe knows 
defaultto find the part she wants, simply by memorizing the position of the links and buttons!  It is abundantly clear and proven that the internet appeals to a child’s inquisitive natur
defaulte and their exploratory learning style; certainly that has been our experience, and it won’t be long before they are better at it than us.  
defaultThere is no doubt that the internet can be useful for children, particularly we have found it helpful for improving
default parts of our older child’s education.  But we are 
defaultvery
default thankful for the strong filters we have in place which allows 
defaultaccess to approved sites only.  This gives my wife and 
defaultI
default opportunity to check the content of sites carefully before allowing them to be vi
defaultsited by our children.  Even so, our children are only allowed to access the internet for timed, monitored periods and we certainly wouldn’t leave them alone during this time.   I know and they know
default—
defaultas we have taught them
default—
defaultthat the internet has hidden d
defaultangers that they are not able to cope with.  
defaultIn addition, too much computer activity tends to make 
defaultour 
defaultchildren less interested in outdoor activities and other necessary skills like writing and drawing.
